{"title_page": "Muslim Bhumihar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n\nThe '''Brahmin''', also locally called pandit, belongs to Brahmin Caste in caste hierarchy found in the state of [[Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Bihar]] in India. The Hindi word beahmin means Landholders in English. The families who became Landlord started calling themselves brahmin. They are a few thousands out of total brahmin population of 10 million (i.e. less than 0.1%). But their existence gives an interesting look into the social and political situation of [[medieval India]].\n\n==Origin==\nThey are originally the Brahmans who were the followers of Lord Parshuram. They have come from Padampur in the distant past. Subsequent to their arrival, they entered into the service of Tikam Deo, the Cheru tribal chieftain of [[Birpur]] and  eventually was awarded his capital and occupying his estate allegedly due to their valour. They later split into three main branches; after the founders Rajdhar Rai, Mukund Rai, and Pithaur Rai. Rajdhar Rai captured Birpur and one of his subdivisions settled in the [[Bara taluka]] of [[Zamania]]. Kinwar Hindu Bhumihars claim to be the descendants of Amog Dixit of Padampur who first settled in Ballia in 1122. \n\n==Present circumstances==\n\nThe community has much in common with the neighbouring [[Sikarwar Khanzada]]s, with whom they intermarry. Unlike Hindu Bhumihars, the Muslim Bhumihar do not practice clan exogamy, and marry close kin. There are, however, still cases of village exogamy.  They are now mainly a community of peasant cultivators, but historically were in possession of most of the [[Bara, Ghazipur|Bara]] of Ghazipur District. The Muslim Bhumihar speak [[Bhojpuri]], although most also understand [[Urdu]]. Each of their settlement contains an informal caste council known as a [[panchayat]], which enforces communal norms as well as resolving intra-community disputes. The \"Muslim Bhumihar\" are [[Sunni]] Muslims, although they practice many folk beliefs.<ref>Kin, clan, raja, and rule : state-hinterland relations in preindustrial India / Richard G. Fox</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n1[[Gazetteer of banaras 1856]]\n\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of India]]\n[[Category:Ghazipur]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Muhajir communities]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n\nThe '''Brahmin''', also locally called pandit, belongs to Brahmin Caste in caste hierarchy found in the state of [[Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Bihar]] in India. The Hindi word beahmin means Landholders in English. The families who became Landlord started calling themselves brahmin. They are a few thousands out of total brahmin population of 10 million (i.e. less than 0.1%). But their existence gives an interesting look into the social and political situation of [[medieval India]].\n\n==Origin==\nThey claim to have come from Padampur in the distant past. Subsequent to their arrival, they entered into the service of Tikam Deo, the Cheru tribal chieftain of [[Birpur]] and  eventually overthrew him, seizing his capital and occupying his estate. They later split into three main branches; after the founders Rajdhar Rai, Mukund Rai, and Pithaur Rai. Rajdhar Rai captured Birpur and one of his subdivisions settled in the [[Bara taluka]] of [[Zamania]], and converted to Islam. Kinwar Hindu Bhumihars claim to be the descendants of Amog Dixit of Padampur who first settled in Ballia in 1122. They convert to Islam.\n\n==Present circumstances==\n\nThe community has much in common with the neighbouring [[Sikarwar Khanzada]]s, with whom they intermarry. Unlike Hindu Bhumihars, the Muslim Bhumihar do not practice clan exogamy, and marry close kin. There are, however, still cases of village exogamy.  They are now mainly a community of peasant cultivators, but historically were in possession of most of the [[Bara, Ghazipur|Bara]] of Ghazipur District. The Muslim Bhumihar speak [[Bhojpuri]], although most also understand [[Urdu]]. Each of their settlement contains an informal caste council known as a [[panchayat]], which enforces communal norms as well as resolving intra-community disputes. The \"Muslim Bhumihar\" are [[Sunni]] Muslims, although they practice many folk beliefs.<ref>Kin, clan, raja, and rule : state-hinterland relations in preindustrial India / Richard G. Fox</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n1[[Gazetteer of banaras 1856]]\n\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Muslim communities of India]]\n[[Category:Ghazipur]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Muhajir communities]]\n", "name_user": "Nhi btaunga", "label": "safe", "comment": "Absolute rubbish which was written in this page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muslim_Bhumihar"}
