riest)|Zechariah]]\n|Television film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2007\n|''Mineurs''\n|Michele Acucella\n|\n|-\n|''[[Der F\u00fcrst und das M\u00e4dchen]]''\n|Count Massimo di Romano\n|Television series;\n8 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" |2008\n|''M\u00e1ri\u00f3, a var\u00e1zsl\u00f3''\n|Mario\n|\n|-\n|''Bastardi''\n|Rene Iuvara\n|\n|-\n|''La rabbia''\n|Mentore\n|\n|-\n|[[Bathory (film)|''Bathory: Countess of Blood'']]\n|[[Matthias, Holy Roman Emperor|King Mathias II of Hungary]]\n|\n|-\n|''Il sangue e la rosa''\n|Umberto Mancini\n|Television series;\n1 episode\n|-\n|''Mein Herz in Chile''\n|Carlos Sanchez\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Television film\n|-\n|''A Night at the Grand Hotel''\n|Ferran Moreno\n|-\n|[[Rosamunde Pilcher|''Rosamunde Pilcher's Four Seasons'']]\n|Max Freeman\n|Television miniseries\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2009\n|''Mord ist mein Gesch\u00e4ft, Liebling''\n|Enrico Puzzo\n|\n|-\n|''[[Palestrina - Prince of Music]]''\n|Domenico Ferrabosco\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2010\n|''[[Augustine: The Decline of the Roman Empire]]''\n|[[Augustine of Hippo]]\n|Television miniseries\n|-\n|''Angelus Hiroshimae''\n|The Hunter\n|\n|-\n|''[[Letters to Juliet]]''\n|Lorenzo Bartolini\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2011\n|[[Rasputin (2011 film)|''Rasputin'']]\n|Narrator\n|\n|-\n|''New Order''\n|Dr. Cornelius Van Morgen\n|\n|-\n|[[Father (2011 film)|''Father'']]\n|Enrico\n|\n|-\n|''[[Cars 2]]''\n|Uncle Topolino\n|\n|-\n|''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n|Roberto Distasio\n|Television series;\n1 episode\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2012\n|''Canepazzo''\n|Alvaro Genta\n|\n|-\n|''A Mem\u00f3ria que me Contam''\n|Paolo\n|\n|-\n|''[[Django Unchained]]''\n|Amerigo Vessepi\n|\n|-\n|''The Woods''\n|Enzo Philipo\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2013\n|''[[Cadences obstin\u00e9es]]''\n|Carmine\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dante's Inferno: An Animated Epic]]''\n|Circles Introduction\n|Italian version only\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2014\n|''Nymph''\n|Niko\n|\n|-\n|[[Love Island (2014 film)|''Love Island'']]\n|Marquis Polesini\n|\n|-\n|''Figli di Maam''\n|Herod\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2016\n|''Il Ragazzo della Giudecca''\n|Salvatore\n|\n|-\n|[[The Lost City of Z (film)|''The Lost City of Z'']]\n|Baron de Gondoriz\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2017\n|[[The Neighborhood (film)|''The Neighborhood'']]\n|Gugliemo\n|\n|-\n|''[[John Wick: Chapter 2]]''\n|Julius\n|\n|-\n|''[[Der Mann aus dem Eis]]''\n|Ditob\n|Stone Age thriller with Rhaetian dialogue.\n|-\n|[[The Time of Their Lives (2017 film)|''The Time of Their Lives'']]\n|Alberto\n|\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|[[Delicious (TV series)|''Delicious'']]\n|Joe Benelli\n|Television series;\n4 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n|''[[The Broken Key]]''\n|Hiram Abif\n|\n|-\n|''[[Red Land - Rosso Istria]]''\n|Professor Ambrosin\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n== Discography ==\n\n*1985 - ''Will Change The World''/''Cambier\u00e0'' (Lovers, LVNP 802, 7\" - with his son Carlo)\n\n{{Portal|Biography|Italy|United Kingdom|Film|Theatre}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|626259}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=140073}}\n\n{{David di Donatello Best Actor}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nero, Franco}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:David di Donatello winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Modena]]\n[[Category:Male Spaghetti Western actors]]\n[[Category:Male Western (genre) film actors]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Italian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Redgrave family]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Franco Nero\n|image        = Franco Nero, 36th Fajr International Film Festival (86250).jpg\n|caption      = Nero in April 2018\n|birth_name   = Francesco Clemente Giuseppe Sparanero\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1941|11|23|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[San Prospero Parmense]], [[Parma]], [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]]\n|occupation   = Actor\n|years_active = 1962\u2013present\n|spouse       = {{marriage|[[Vanessa Redgrave]]|2006}}\n|children     = [[Carlo Gabriel Nero]]\n}}\n'''Francesco Clemente Giuseppe Sparanero''' (born 23 November 1941), better known by his [[stage name]] '''Franco Nero''', is an [[Italians|Italian]] actor. He is best known for his [[breakthrough role]] as the [[Django (character)|title character]] in [[Sergio Corbucci]]'s [[Spaghetti Western]] film ''[[Django (1966 film)|Django]]'' (1966), a role that he reprised in [[Nello Rossati]]'s ''[[Django Strikes Again]]'' (1987).\n\nSince then, he has performed over 200 leading and supporting roles in a wide variety of films and television programmes in both Italy and abroad, in genres ranging from ''[[poliziotteschi]]'', to [[Action film|action]], to [[Drama (film and television)|drama]], to [[War film|war]], and [[Musical film|musicals]]. These include ''[[The Bible: In the Beginning...]]'' (1966), ''[[Camelot (film)|Camelot]]'' (1967), ''[[The Day of the Owl (film)|The Day of the Owl]]'' (1968), ''[[The Mercenary (film)|The Mercenary]]'' (1968),  ''[[Battle of Neretva (film)|Battle of Neretva]]'' (1969), ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'' (1970), ''[[Compa\u00f1eros]]'' (1970), ''[[Confessions of a Police Captain]]'' (1971), ''[[Keoma (film)|Keoma]]'' (1976), ''[[Hitch-Hike (film)|Hitch-Hike]]'' (1977), ''[[Force 10 from Navarone (film)|Force 10 from Navarone]]'' (1978), ''[[Enter the Ninja]]'' (1981), ''[[Die Hard 2]]'' (1990), ''[[Letters to Juliet]]'' (2010) and ''[[John Wick: Chapter 2]]'' (2017). He also played the narrator in the film ''[[Rasputin (2011 film)|Rasputin]]'' (2010), directed by [[Louis Nero]], and voiced the character of [[List of Cars characters#Uncle Topolino|Uncle Topolino]] in the animated film ''[[Cars 2]]'' (2011) directed by [[John Lasseter]] and co-directed by Brad Lewis. In 2012, Nero made a [[cameo appearance]] in [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s ''[[Django Unchained]].''\n\nAccording to Deadline Hollywood, Nero is expected to appear in the dark comedy feature film ''The Immortalist'' in 2020, along with Sherilyn Fenn, Paul Rodriguez, Aries Spears, and Jeff DuJardin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/rachel-true-sean-gunn-agnes-sherilyn-fenn-franco-nero-immortalist-cameron-douglas-elisabeth-rohm-the-runner-1202814905/|title=Rachel True, Sean Gunn Join \u2018Agnes\u2019; Sherilyn Fenn, Franco Nero Topline \u2018Immortalist\u2019; Cameron Douglas, Elisabeth R\u00f6hm In \u2018The Runner\u2019|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|last2=N'Duka|first2=Amanda|date=2019-12-20|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> Directed by Vlad Kozlov. \n\nNero is known for his ties to the [[Redgrave family]], and has had a long-standing relationship with [[Vanessa Redgrave|Vanessa]], which began during the filming of ''Camelot''. They were married in 2006.\n\n==Early life==\nFrancesco Clemente Giuseppe Sparanero<ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.mymovies.it/biografia/?a=2622 Franco Nero] in MyMovies</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/section/movies|title=Movies|publisher=|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{in lang|it}} [https://movies.nytimes.com/person/52262/Franco-Nero Franco Nero] in CinemaItaliano.info</ref><ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.cinemastore.it/index.php?target=actor&actorId=1835&role=1 Franco Nero] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120721214909/http://www.cinemastore.it/index.php?target=actor&actorId=1835&role=1 |date=21 July 2012 }} in Cinemastore Italy</ref><ref>{{in lang|it}} [https://archive.is/20130126061425/http://www.hollywood.com/celebrity/193260/Franco_Nero_Biography Francoo Nero] Biography in Hollywood.com</ref> was born in [[San Prospero Parmense]] ([[province of Parma]], [[Emilia-Romagna]]), the son of a commissioned officer in the [[Carabinieri]],<ref name=ref1>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20072275,00.html|title=He Lost His Guenevere, Vanessa Redgrave, but Franco Nero Found His Camelot Back in Italy|author=Ann Pearce|publisher=People}}</ref> originally from [[San Severo]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Redazione online|title=San Severo, cittadinanza a Franco Nero|url=http://corrieredelmezzogiorno.corriere.it/napoli/notizie/spettacoli/2011/5-dicembre-2011/san-severo-cittadinanza-franco-nero-1902419357562.shtml|accessdate=17 April 2013|newspaper=[[Corriere del Mezzogiorno]]|date=5 December 2011}}</ref> He grew up in [[Bedonia, Italy|Bedonia]] and in [[Milan, Italy|Milan]]. He studied briefly at the Economy and Trade faculty of the local university, before leaving to study at the [[Piccolo Teatro di Milano]].\n\n==Acting career==\n[[File:Franco Nero (Django).jpg|right|thumb|250px|Franco Nero as the title character in ''Django'' (1966)]]\nNero's first film role was a small part in ''[[Pelle viva]]'' (1962),<ref>{{cite news|last1=Paolo Russo|title=\"Io, Django e Fassbinder\" Franco Nero, che grande attore|url=http://firenze.repubblica.it/cronaca/2014/11/16/news/io_e_la_mia_fortuna_fra_b-movie_e_bunuel_incontro_col_franco_nero_che_non_t_aspetti-100732603/|accessdate=6 July 2016|work=[[La Repubblica]]|date=16 November 2014}}</ref> and he had his first lead role in [[Sergio Corbucci]]'s ''[[Django (1966 film)|Django]]'' (1966) a [[spaghetti western]] and one of his best-known films. In 1966 from ''Django'' he went on to appear in eight more films released that year including ''[[Texas, Adios]]'' (1966) and ''[[Massacre Time]]''.\n\nIn 1967, he appeared in ''[[Camelot (film)|Camelot]]'' as [[Lancelot]], where he met his longtime romantic partner, and later on in life his wife, [[Vanessa Redgrave]]. Following this he appeared in [[the mafia]] film  ''[[Il giorno della civetta (film)|Il giorno della civetta]]'' opposite [[Claudia Cardinale]] released in 1968.\n\nA lack of proficiency in English tended to limit these roles, although he also appeared in other English-language films including ''[[The Virgin and the Gypsy (film)|The Virgin and the Gypsy]]'' (1970), ''[[Force 10 from Navarone (film)|Force 10 from Navarone]]'' (1978), ''[[Enter the Ninja]]'' (1981) and ''[[Die Hard 2]]'' (1990).\n\nAlthough often typecast in films like ''[[Deaf Smith & Johnny Ears|Los amigos]]'' (1973) or ''[[Keoma (film)|Keoma]]'' (1976) he has attempted an impressive range of characters, such as [[Abel]] in [[John Huston]]'s epic ''[[The Bible: In The Beginning]]'' (1966), the humiliated engineer out for revenge in ''[[Street Law (film)|Street Law]]'', the gay lieutenant in ''[[Querelle]]'' (1982) and [[Cinema of Serbia|Serbian]] mediaeval hero in ''[[The Falcon (film)|The Falcon]]'' (1983). He has appeared in over 150 films, and has written, produced and starred in one: ''[[Jonathan degli orsi]]'' (1993).<ref>[http://www.1kult.com/2010/02/12/linterview-exclusive-de-franco-nero/ Franco Nero Interview from 1Kult.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100430191754/http://www.1kult.com/2010/02/12/linterview-exclusive-de-franco-nero/ |date=30 April 2010 }} (English subtitled)</ref>\n\nMore recently, he starred in Hungarian director {{Interlanguage link multi|Koltay G\u00e1bor|hu}}'s ''[[The Conquest (1996 film)|Honfoglal\u00e1s (Conquest)]]'' in 1996, in ''[[Li chiamarono... briganti!]]'' (1999) by [[Pasquale Squitieri]] and subsequently in Koltay's ''Sacra Corona (Holy Crown)'' in 2001.\n\nIn 2009 he played an eccentric author called \"Mario Puzzo\" in ''[[Mord ist mein Gesch\u00e4ft, Liebling]]'' (\"Murder is my trade, darling\", Italian title \"Tesoro, sono un killer\"). German critics found his performance was the best part of the film: \"Having Franco Nero playing in this film is really a great joy - it is only regrettable that after his appearances there is still so much film left.\"<ref>\"Dass Franco Nero in diesem Film mitspielt, macht wirklich gro\u00dfen Spa\u00df \u2013 schade nur, dass nach seinen Auftritten noch so viel Film \u00fcbrig ist.\" {{Cite news|url= http://www.filmzentrale.com/rezis2/mordistmeingeschaeftlieblingob.htm|last=Oliver Baumgarten|title= Mord ist mein Gesch\u00e4ft, liebling| newspaper=Filmzentrale| accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Nero appeared in the film ''[[Letters to Juliet]]'' with Redgrave. In 2011 he appeared as a guest star on the season 13 premiere episode of [[Law and Order SVU]]. His character, although Italian, was based on [[Dominique Strauss-Kahn]]. In the same year, he received a star on the [[Italian Walk of Fame]] in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada.<ref>{{cite news |last=Yuen |first=Jenny |url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/09/05/italian-walk-of-fame-honours-stars |title=Italian Walk of Fame honours stars |date=5 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Nero made a [[cameo appearance]] in the film ''[[Django Unchained]]'' in one scene alongside [[Jamie Foxx]], who stars as Django Freeman in the film. In the scene Nero plays the original Django, an Italian Mandingo Fighter manager. Nero's Django then questions Foxx's Django about how his name is spelled, and asks him to spell it, referencing a scene from Nero's role as Django in the original ''[[Django (1966 film)|Django]]'' film. Upon learning that their names are spelled the same way, Nero's Django says \"I know\" to Foxx's Django.\n\nIn 2016 and 2017 he has interpreted [[Gabriele Tinti (writer)|Gabriele Tinti]]'s poetry giving voice to the masterpieces in the [[National Roman Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beniculturali.it/mibac/export/MiBAC/sito-MiBAC/Contenuti/MibacUnif/Eventi/visualizza_asset.html_2021732403.html|title=Franco Nero legge 'Il Pugile' di Gabriele Tinti|first=|last=System|website=www.beniculturali.it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.it/evento/franco-nero-reads-songs-of-stone-by-gabriele-tinti-685650401?#franco-nero-attends-the-songs-of-stone-by-gabriele-tinti-at-museo-picture-id627638616|title=Franco Nero Reads 'Songs Of Stone' By Gabriele Tinti|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHis romantic involvement with British actress [[Vanessa Redgrave]] began in 1966 when they met on the set of ''[[Camelot (film)|Camelot]]''. In 1969, they had a son, Carlo Gabriel Redgrave Sparanero (known professionally as [[Carlo Gabriel Nero]]), a screenwriter and director. After separating for many years, during which they both had relationships with other people, they reunited and married on 31 December 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturenews/7817915/Vanessa-Redgrave-speaks-about-marriage-to-second-husband-for-the-first-time.html |title=Vanessa Redgrave speaks about marriage to second 'husband' for the first time |publisher=Telegraph |date=11 June 2010 |accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> Carlo Nero directed Redgrave in the cinematic adaptation of [[Wallace Shawn]]'s play ''[[The Fever (2004 film)|The Fever]]''.\n\nNero dated actresses [[Catherine Deneuve]], [[Goldie Hawn]] and [[Ursula Andress]] in the 1970s.<ref>\"Jack O'Brian's Mainland\". ''Honolulu Star-Bulletin.'' Honolulu, Hawaii. February 11, 1970. p. 49.</ref><ref>Jack O'Brian (September 8, 1975). [https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/5412448 Goldie and Vanessa's Oldie]. ''Lebanon Daily News''</ref><ref>Page Six (9 January 1986). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19860109&id=JQROAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MJwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4375,2221586&hl=en Kiss & Tell]. ''New Straits Times''.</ref> \nIn 1994, Nero walked his future stepdaughter [[Natasha Richardson]] (1963\u20132009) down the aisle when she married actor [[Liam Neeson]]. Her father, [[Tony Richardson]], had died in 1991.\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1965\n|''[[I Knew Her Well]]''\n|Italo\n|\n|-\n|''[[Gli uomini dal passo pesante|The Tramplers]]''\n|Charley Garvey\n|\n|-\n|''[[Wild, Wild Planet]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Lt. Jake Jacowitz\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" |1966\n|''[[War of the Planets (1966)|War of the Planets]]''\n|\n|-\n|''Hired Killer''\n|Tony Lo Bello\n|\n|-\n|[[Django (1966 film)|''Django'']]\n|[[Django (character)|Django]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[Massacre Time]]''\n|Tom Corbett\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Third Eye (1966 film)|The Third Eye]]''\n|Mino Alberti\n|\n|-\n|''[[Texas, Adios]]''\n|Sheriff Burt Sullivan\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Bible: In the Beginning...]]''\n|[[Abel]]\n|First American film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1967\n|''[[Man, Pride and Vengeance]]''\n|Don Jos\u00e9\n|\n|-\n|''[[Camelot (film)|Camelot]]''\n|[[Lancelot du Lac]]\n|Singing voice by [[Gene Merlino]]\nNominated - [[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year \u2013 Actor|Golden Globe Award for Most Promising Newcomer \u2013 Male]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |1968\n|''[[The Day of the Owl (film)|The Day of the Owl]]'' \n|Capt. Claudio Bellodi\n|Won - [[David di Donatello for Best Actor|David di Donatello Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n|''[[Sardinia Kidnapped]]''\n|Gavino\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Mercenary (film)|The Mercenary]]''\n|Sergei \"Polack\" Kowalski\n|\n|-\n|''[[A Quiet Place in the Country]]''\n|Leonardo Ferri\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1969\n|''[[The Fifth Day of Peace]]''\n|Ensign Bruno Grauber\n|\n|-\n|''[[Detective Belli]]''\n|Detective Stefano Belli\n|\n|-\n|''[[Battle of Neretva (film)|Battle of Neretva]]''\n|Capt. Michele Riva\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |1970\n|''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]''\n|Horacio\n|\n|-\n|[[The Virgin and the Gypsy (film)|''The Virgin and the Gypsy'']]\n|The Gypsy\n|Nominated - [[Laurel Awards|Golden Laurel Award for Star of Tomorrow, Male]]\n|-\n|''[[Dropout (film)|Dropout]]''\n|Bruno Grazza \n|\n|-\n|''[[Compa\u00f1eros]]''\n|Yodlaf Peterson\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |1971\n|''[[The Case Is Closed, Forget It]]'' \n|Vanzi\n|\n|-\n|''[[Confessions of a Police Captain]]''\n|Deputy D.A. Traini\n|Won - [[Globo d'oro|Italian Golden Globe Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n|''[[The Fifth Cord]]''\n|Andrea Bild\n|\n|-\n|''[[La vacanza]]''\n|Osiride\n|\n|-\n|''[[Long Live Your Death]]''\n|Dmitri Vassilovich Orlowsky \n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1972\n|''[[Pope Joan (1972 film)|Pope Joan]]''\n|[[Louis II of Italy]]\n|\n|-\